{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_lucretia_ver01/data/sn86086852/00271768990/1908061801/0009.xml":{"full_text":"FORTY-SECOND YEAR. NO. 39.\nPurity and\nReliability\nIN a matter so important as the med\nicine that you have to take when\nyou are sick it is well to know some\nthing about it.\nAs druggists it is our constant duty\nto buy and dispense the drugs which\nenter into the medicines prescribed by\nphysicians and taken by the general\npublic.\nWe have won a considerable reputa\ntion for the skilful and accurate man\nner in which we compound medicines\nprescribed by the physicians.\nAt MESEROLE HORN S\nPhone 19\nOxfords\nFor Ladies, Gents,\nand Children.\nBrown,\nTan.\n()xhlood,\nPatent Leather,\nWhite Duck,\nWith Fancy I losiery\nto match.\nGet ready for the HOT\nWEATHER, at store of\nJ. F. IIENDRA.\nMillinery Sale.\nCLOSING OTT at reduced\nprices: A good assortment of\nladies\u2019 and children's Trim\nmed Hats.\nA. MASTER\u2019S.\nMineral Point. Wls. 3S\nR A 1 S E YO U R CAL VE S\nWITHOUT MILK\nMilk is worth too much this year\nto feed it to the calves.\nMartin\u2019s\n(2alf Feed\nis a perfect milk substitute and good\ncalves can be raised on it and water.\nIt is almost wholly digestible, and is\nespecially adapted to the delicate\ndigestive organs of young animals.\nSPECIAL OFFER\nBuy 100 tt>s of Martin\u2019s Calf feed and\nget a coupon good for 25c at three\ndifferent stores in town. Yours truly,\nJ NO. C. MARTIN CO.\nProspecting\nMachinery\nof all kinds built and\ninstalled bv\nGalena Iron Works\nCompany\nGalena. Illinois.\nP L ATI' EVIL LE, WISCO NSIN.\nWe make our own machinery\nand can furnish Repair Parts\nAT ONCE.\nOur machinery is adapted\nto the needs of this district.\nGALENA IRON WORKS CO.\nIOWA COUNTY DEMOCRAT.\nState Historical Society\nSales on the Mineral Point Dairy\nBoard.\nThe Dairy Board met on Tuesday\nafternoon, with a good attendance of\nmembers. The market was active,\nand sales were as follows:\n494 twins (a 11c.\nThe next meeting will be on Tues\nday afternoon, June 30.\nThe sales at the meeting of one year\nago were 377 twins (a life.\nAlumni Party.\nThe annual party of the Mineral\nPoint high school was held at Masonic\nTemple last Friday night and was\nvery pleasant and successful. Mayor\nEdward Brown was toast-master, and\nthe program included:\nToast to theclass\u2014Miss Temperance\nKnight.\nResponse\u2014Daniel McWilliams.\nSongs by Mias Eunice Blewett and\nJoseph Maust.\nAddresses by W. A. Jones, E. C.\nFiedler, J. N. Treweek, and Will\nBohan.\nBusiness Outlook Improving.\nThe weekly financial letter of Henry\nClews Cos., New York, says that\ngeneral business shows an improving\ntendency. Confidence is gaining\nsteadily, and, while summer may\nprove a period of quiet, there is well\ngrounded hope that with a good har\nvest, and with political uncertanties\nout of the way, the volume of trade\nwill show steady improvement in the\ncoming fall and winter months. As\nfor the stock market, moderate flucta\ntions may be anticipated. No serious\nbreak is probable, nor is a sharp ad\nvance likely at this time when favor\nable elements have been so fully\ndiscounted.\nBadger Club Dance.\nThe Badger club will hold their\nnext dance in the Masonic Temple,\nFriday evening, June 19.\nBazaar and Pantry Sale.\nThe Dorcas society will have an\nApron Bazaar and Pantry Sale in the\nold National Bank building on Sat\nurday, June 27. We will have for\nsale Bread and Rolls, Pasties, Cake,\nCookies and Doughnuts. 39w2\nSouth Dakota Lands.\nJ. D. James has just returned from\nSouth Dakota, where he made a sale\nof land to John Stevens of Linden.\nMr. James says that no state in the\nUnion can show a better prospect for\na good crop than South Dakota can.\nif there is a second lowa it is South\nDakota, and the place for you young\nmen to get a nice farm. It will not be\nmany years before that portion of the\nstate east of the Missouri river will be\nall settled, and land will be as high\nin price as Wisconsin or lowa. Now\nto my old Mineral Point friends, I\nwill make excursions the first and\nthird Tuesday of each month to South\nDakota, and I invite you all that want\nto get a farm to go with me. I will\nput my time against your time, and\nshow you one of the best states in the\nUnion where you can raise corn as\nwell as in lowa. Anyone who wants\nto go, leave word with Crawford\nBrothers.\nA Large and fine line of\nHAMMOCKS\nMineral Point. J. J. HANSCOM CO.\nP\\ONT let yourself be led to believe that\nany mail order house will give $1.25 of\ngoods for sl. Bring your dollar to the\nWHITE MEAT MARKET AND\nGROCERY STORE\nand if they can\u2019t give more and better goods\nthan any mail order house we will gladly re\nfund your money. Give us a call.\nJ. GORGEN SONS.\nJ. J. Penhallegon Go.\nA large stock of\n\u201cDaiii\" Hay Loaders,\n\u201cDain\u201d Side Delivery Rakes,\n\u201cDaiii\u201d Mowers--\\ ertical Lift.\nFine Buggies and Wagons a specialty. Xo poor grade\nmaterial. The best that can be had.\nPARIS GREEN\nHardware, Stoves and Ranges. Also a line of buggy whips,\nand carriage and buggy Harness. The best goods at the\nlowest prices. See us before buying.\nJ. J. PENHALLEGON HARDWARE CO.\nWare-rooms in building formerly occupied Fred. L. Cork. Phone 03, two rings.\nMINERAL POINT, WISCONSIN. THURSDAY, JUNE 18, 1908.\nHenry G. Rogers,\na life long and widely known resident\n!of Milwaukee, and a veteran of the\ncivil war, died at his summer h*me at\nOconomowoc at 10:30 Wednesday\nmorniny.\nMr. Rogers was an uncle of Mrs. J.\nJ. Hanscom of Mineral Point.\nThe J. B. Pittz Residence\nI in this city will be found in the list of\nproperty advertised for sale by the\nMineral Point Real Estate Agency.\nIt is for rent subject to sale.\nAn Ice Cream Social\nwill be held at Pleasant View next\nTuesday evening, June 23. If the\nweather is unfavorable, it will be held\nthe following evening. All are wel\ncome.\nPublic Take Notice.\nAll the Barbers of the city of Min\neral Point have agreed to \u201cclose\u201d\ntheir places of business on Saturday,\nJuly 4, 1908, at 1 p. m. sharp, and\nstay closed for the remainder of that\nday. There will poscively be no work\ndone after this hour. Per Committee.\nUnclaimed Letters.\nMineral Point, June 11.\u2014Letters\naddressed as follows remain unclaimed at the\nMineral Point postofflee:\nMarie MaGould, Miss Ban Collins,\nH. J. Smith, Mayme Carey,\nDan Austin, Mrs. Sarah Harvey.\nIn calling for above please say Advertised,\nB. T. Prideacx, Postmaster.\nAt the Methodist Episcopal\nChurch\nnext Sunday morning Mr. Phil Allen\nJr,, will preach. In the evening the\nthe Rev. Wm. Croft will occupy the\npulpit.\nChange of Business.\nOwing to the change in the firm of\nWalters Suthers all outstanding\nbills against said firm should be pre\nsented for payment, and all persons\nindebted to the firm are requested to\nand settle at once.\nFred U. Walters.\nFrank Suthers.\nReduced Prices for Wall Paper\nfor the next thirty days at Hanscora\u2019s.\nHouse and Lot for $1,600.\nDuring the year we have had many\ninquiries by intending perchasers for\na small dwelling house centrally lo\ncated. Such a place has just been\nplaced with us for sale.\nCrawford Bros.\nDR. BREWER SON\u2019S\nAPPOINTMENT FOR CONSULTATION.\nMineral Point, Wisconsin, U. S.\nHotel, on Friday July 24.\nDarlington, Wisconsin, Hotel Gor\ndon, on Saturday, July 25.\nFARMERS;\nWill Dick have received an\nother shipment of wagon um\nbrellas worth sl.7seach, and are\nselling them at SI.OO each, as\nthey bear our advertisement.\nBetter get one for your milk wagon,\nonly a few left. This is less than\nwholesale price.\nCORRKLL MARTIN.\nGundry Gray Cos.\nMINERAL POINT WISCONSIN.\nNew Pair\nFop a Hole\nTroubled with your Kockinjs? Wt\u2019re t>\u2018 I\nmn article that we guarantee againat hole* or\nript for six month*. No Us\" or' jodi\u2019\u2019 it I\nbole develop! you get a new pair.\nA\nThe newest idea in stockings.' Made\nto wear; not That\u2019s\nwe giiiUU\nabiolutely. ri t H\nA line of new neckwear just\nreceived.\nPanama hats in the new\nshapes for this season.\nMen\u2019s summer underwear; in\nknee length drawers and\nshort sleeve shirts.\nNew colored felt hats placed\non sale this week.\nGundry Gray Cos.\nMINERAL POINT. WIS.\nPRINTING INDUSTRY,\nHoWs Seventh Place Among Our\nManufactures.\nTHE TARIFF AND NEWSPAPERS\nOppressive Dingle/ Duty Strangling\nan Important Business\u2014Herman Bid\nder Writes on the Contest For Free\nPaper.\nThe publishing and printing industry\nholds the seventh place anting the\nmanufacturing industries in the United\nStates, representing an annual product\nof over one-half billion dollars. This\nImportant industry Is being strangled\nby the oppressive duties of the Dingley\ntariff upon the one article indispensa\nble to its production, print paper, and\non wood pulp, which is used in the\nmanufacture of paper. Yielding to\nrepresentations convincing him of the\ndetrimental effects of these duties,\nPresident Roosevelt has in a special\nmessage to congress recommended\ntheir repeal. What is the response of\nthe defenders of the protective tariff\nin that body? As voiced by the speak\ner himself, Mr. Cannon, the grand mar\nshal of the anti-revisionist forces, it\nroad: \u201cThe duty on print paper Is 15\nper cent ad valorem and has been the\nsame since 1890, under the McKinley\nlaw, the Wilson law and the Dingley\nlaw, covering a period of eighteen\nyears. If the claim of the\npublishers (as to large advances in\nprices within the last few months) is\ncorrect, the advance in the price is not\ndue to the duty, but resulting from the\nIllegal trust and combination. If the\nsmall duty were repealed It would not\ninterfere with the illegal trust agree\nment.\"\nThis argument is disingenuous, as\ncan be clearly shown by the following\nfacts: The duty on print paper under\nthe Dingle}' tariff is not 15 per cent\nad valorem, but $0 per ton on paper\nvalued at not above 2 cents per pound\nand $8 per ton upon paper valued\nabove 2 cents per pound. At the time\nof the enactment of the Dingley law\nprint paper was sold at the mill at\n$1.75 per hundred pounds and in some\nInstances in the city of New York at\n$1.65, or $1.35 at the Canadian giilL\nThat is $27 per ton. Placing the duty\non the old basis of 15 per cent ad valo\nrem, as is claimed by the speaker, this\nshould have made the amount of the\nduty' about $4, so that this duty was\nby the Dingley tariff increased 50 per\ncent. At the same time the duty on\nwood pulp was increased from 10 per\ncent, or an average of $1.20 per ton, to\nSI.C7 per ton.\nThe trust is the offspring of the\ntariff. Especially has this been proved\nin the case of the paper trust. While\nthe paper schedule of the Dingley tariff\nwas under consideration the committee\non ways and means was formally\nwarned by John Norris, an acknowl\nedged authority, of the fact that in an\nticipation of the hnai adoption of the\nbill \u201cthe news paper manufacturers of\nthe United States have perfected their\narrangement for a combination by\nwhich ever}' newspaper should be at\nthe mercy of a central selling agency\nand by which the price of news print\npaper shall be raised and by which\nthese gentlemen shall derive an addi\ntional profit of from five to six million\ndollars out of their Investment and\nthereby tax knowledge and diminish\nthe educational possibilities of the\nnewspaper press.\u201d\nMr. Norris went so far as to name\nthe men who were at that time making\nplans to create the future paper trust\nof the United States\u2014ex-Congressman\nRussell, ex-Senator Warner Miller and\nHugh Chisholm. The Dingley bill was\nenacted in July. 1897. The Internation\nal Paper company was organized the\nfollowing January, and the three paper\nmanufacturers who had appeared be\nfore the committee and secured the\nprint paper and wood pulp tariff\u2014\nMessrs. Russell. Warner Miller and\nChisholm\u2014became its executive offi\ncers. Is not this conclusive proof that\nthe paper trust was born and its crea\ntion made possible by the tariff? The\ngovernment has dissolved as an unlaw\nful combination the General Paper\ncompany. Its business has been con\nftguedjir other confttaatong, and so\nit will go on. no matter fiow many\ncombinations shall be stopped by the\ngovernment. There is only one remedy\n\u2014expunge the cause of the trust; re\npeal the tax HERMAN RIDDER,\nAbout \u201cConserving Resources.\u201d\nTo resolve that we must conserve\nnational resources Is good. To do it\nwould be better. The first step is to\nknock down the tariff wall which, by\nkeeping foreign coal, Iron, lumber, etc.,\nout of the United States, has compelled\nus to prematurely exhaust our limited\nstores of these necessities, while at tne\nsame time increasing the tribute we\nmust pay to the trusts that monopolke\nthese gifts of nature.\nTHE WHITE HOUSE\nMineral Point\u2019s Bargain Center.\nA FEW SPECIALS\nthat are SPECIALS.\nAll our\nLadies\u2019 White Lawn Waists.\nin short or length sleeves, at\nExactly Half Price.\nA few\nLadies\u2019 Spring Jackets and Skirts\nnot many, at a\nGreat Big Cut in Price.\n15 pieces 32-inch blue and red percales, 7c yard, or 10\nyards for G7c.\nSun Hats, Sun Bonnets, Babv Bonnets, etc., to close, at\nACTUAL COST.\nThe White House. W. J. PFNILALLEGON, Prop.\nNOW IS THE TIME\nand this is the place for\nVT* r li fl\nSTRAWBERRIES\nFor sale by the box, or by the case for canning.\nTHE JAMES BREWER CO.\nPhone 4. Mineral Point\nNew Hardware Store\nHORN BROS.,\nHigh Street, Mineral Point, opposite Post Office.\nWill keep a full lines of Hardware, Stoves and Tinware,\nincluding the line of\nPeninsular Cook Stoves and Ranges,\nJewell Gasoline Stoves,\nThe celebrated O. V. B. Cutlery and Mechanics Tools.\nTin shop in connection. Repairing a specialty. Give us a trial.\nApril 23, 1908. HORN BROS.\nSpecial Piano Sale.\nIn order to reduce my stock of PIANOS, I will for\na short time only sell them at\nGreatly Reduced Prices.\nI have five different makes to select from, and can\nprice you a piano from $150.00 to $4-00.00. Call\nand see the\nBest Line of Pianos\never shown here, and see how cheaply\u2019 you can buy a\nGOOD PIANO if you buy it at the right place,\nMALGER\u2019S JEWELRY PIANO STORE\nMineral Point Wis. 38tt\nPlain What Sherman Would Do,\nIn ISS9 John Sherman said: \u201cThe\nprimary object of a protective tariff Is\nto secure the fullest competition by In\ndividuals and corporations in domestic\nproductions. If such individuals or cor\nporations combined to advance the\nprice of the domestic product and to\nprevent the free result of open and\nfair competition, I would without a\nmoment\u2019s hesitation reduce the duties\nof foreign goods competing with them\nin order to break down the combina\ntion.\"\nA Pound of Coffee\nand a glass or china dish only 25c at\nThe Toay Grocery Cos.\n$1.25 PEE YEAH IN ADVANCE.\n100,000\nPost Cards\ncarried in stock, wholesale and\nretail. I ship cards to all parts\nol the U. S., and buy in thous\nands. Buy your cards here\nand get designs not found in\nany other place. We are head\nquarters and give you cards\nfor less money. A W THOMA\nINSECTS\nare swarming around\nus in large numbers.\nGuard against them by using\nthe best\nParis Green,\nInsect Powder,\nLondon Purple,\nMoth Balls, etc.\nFor sale at\nIVEY\u2019S\nPHARMACY.\nA stnnMbMs a I way ready!\nA stove that makes no smoke, smell or\nashes!\nA safe stove! An economical stove! A\nclean stove!\nA stove that requires no skill to oper\nate it!\nA stove which has revolutionized\n\u201ccooking,\u201d and has transformed\nthe drudgery of the kitchen work\ninto a pleasant pastime.\nA \u201cQuick Meal\u201d Stove will do any and\nall work that can be done on a wood\nOr coal stove, only with the differ\nence that the \u201cQuick Meal\u201d docs it\n.quicker, cneaper and in a more agree\nable and reliable way.\nSOLD DY\nN. T. MARTIN EST.\nMineral Point, Wis. Phono 25\nWANTS.\